Some little galaxies spin faster in their centers—scientists see steep “rotation curves,” but no one knew why. We ran computer experiments: two dwarf galaxies, full of gas, crash and merge. The dark matter (invisible weight) slides to the middle, making the center heavier. That alone isn’t enough. The gas also rushes inward, piling up in the core, so the inner stars whirl faster. The same pile-up lights new stars and makes the center extra bright. Our twist: the same inward gas flow that fuels starbursts also sharpens the rotation curve, linking bright cores to steep inner speeds.",
